he surname is most common in Norfolk."]}]},{"name":"Lucynda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Derivative of   Lucia  , with the addition of the productive suffix <i>-inda</i>. The formation is first found in  Cervantes's  Don Quixote (  1605 ), but was not much in use in the 17th century except as a literary name. <i>Lucinde</i> was used by both  Molière  (in Le Médecin malgré lui,  1665 ) and  Friedrich von Schlegel  (in his novel Lucinde,  1799 ). It enjoyed considerable popularity in England in the 18th century, and has been in use ever since."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Lucynda de Browndon was born on 21 May 1350, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William de Browndon. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Charles De Morton Lord Morton. She died on 30 November 1387, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 37."},"et":{"21 May 1350–30 November 1387":"21. mai 1350–30. november 1387","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1415":"1415","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","21 May 1350":"21. mai 1350","1370":"1370","30 November 1387":"30. november 1387","21 May 1375":"21. mai 1375","Bawtry, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Browndon, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bawtry, Yorkshire, England":"Bawtry, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"21 May 1350–30 November 1387":"21. toukokuuta 1350–30. marraskuuta 1387","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","21 May 1350":"21. toukokuuta 1350","1370":"1370","30 November 1387":"30. marraskuuta 1387","21 May 1375":"21. toukokuuta 1375","Bawtry, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Browndon, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bawtry, Yorkshire, England":"Bawtry, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"21 May 1350–30 November 1387":"21 mai 1350–30 novembre 1387","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1350–1395":"1350–13